    Test 1 (Weeks 1 - 3) Identify the type of study described below:   Title:  The efficacy of a tart cherry juice blend in preventing the symptoms of muscle damage Purpose:  To test the efficacy of a tart cherry juice blend in preventing the symptoms of exercise induced muscle damage Methods:  This was a randomized, double blind, placebo controlled study.  Fourteen male college students drank 12 fl ounces of a cherry juice blend or a placebo for eight consecutive days.  A bout of strenuous exercise was performed on the fourth day of the supplementation.  Muscle strength, pain and tenderness was measured after the activity.  Results:  Strength loss and pain were significantly less in the cherry juice trial verses the placebo Conclusion:  This data shows the efficacy for this cherry juice in decreasing some of the symptoms of exercise induced muscle damage.     Multiple Choice false question-issues-report\main.js 2018-06-13T11:11:50-06:00

    Test 1 (Weeks 1 - 3) The strength of the evidence for the study posted below is limited (weak). Review the study and answer the question below.  Purpose of Study: To determine the effect of a high-fat, low-carbohydrate diet on the performance of well-trained cyclists. Participants: Five well-trained male cyclists. Methods: All five participants were prescribed a balanced diet to provide adequate calories and micronutrients for one week. At the end of the week, a pedal test of maximal oxygen uptake (VO2max) was conducted to measure time to exhaustion. The cyclists were then prescribed a high-fat, low-carbohydrate diet for 4 weeks to initiate ketosis (still supplemented for appropriate micronutrient intake). At the end of those 4 weeks, the cyclists repeated the pedal test of VO2max. Results:  The mean time to exhaustion was 147 minutes after week 1 and 151 minutes after 4 weeks on the low-carbohydrate diet. No clinical or biochemical evidence showed that the cyclists had low-blood sugar at the end of the 4 week low-carbohydrate diet. Conclusion: The exercise of endurance athletes was not compromised by four weeks of ketosis. Further research is needed due to the results are inconsistent with previous studies.  All of the following are reasons this study is considered to have limited strength EXCEPT Multiple Choice false question-issues-report\main.js 2018-06-13T11:11:50-06:00
